title: Bertha Landes mayoral campaign poster, ca. 1926
Olympic Hotel under construction, June 14, 1924
AFL Labor Temple entrance, ca. 1950
description: The temple was constructed in 1942.

title: Hilde McAuslan, Washington State champion golfer, August 19, 1934
description: Transcribed from photograph: "SEA: 1110. Young Seattle star retains golf crown. Seattle, Washington.- Hilde McAuslan, brilliant young Seattle golfer went through the Washington State Championship contest in nearly far [sic] form to retain her hold on the state title, beating her final rival 14 up and 12 to go. Photo shows Seattle's own Hilda the perfect stylist. Direct service...8/20/34. Exclusive..." Seattle Times articles from August 19 state that the championship took place at the Broadmoor Golf Course.

title: Art Ahonon and Tom Yelich of the University of Washington football team, September 24, 1934
description: Transcribed from photograph: "SEA 1180: Look what Art Ahonen brought back from Ironwood Michigan. Seattle, Washington. - Art Ahonen big end of University of Washington for the third year has just reported to coach Phelan. The boss needed a center and art brought one for him, all the way form Ironwood, Michigan. He is Tom Yelich at the left in this photograph. Art is telling him to look like Ironwood. Direct service...9/24/34..."

title: View north on 2nd Ave. from Yesler Way, ca. 1923
description: Transcribed from photograph: "The downtown business section, Seattle. Looking north up 2nd Ave, with Elliott Bay and the Olympic Mountains to the west." Photo is likely taken from Smith Tower. The Mehlhorn and Empire buildings appear on the right.

title: University of Washington Shipping Board School, 1918
description: Transcribed from photograph: "U.S. Shipping Board School. U of W. 1918." The Shipping Board School was a free program in Marine Engineering established at the University of Washington by the United States Shipping Board.

title: Yesler home near 1st Ave. and Yesler Way, 1860
description: The same photograph is appears in the Prosch Seattle Views Collection at the University of Washington with the following description: "This is the oldest or first known photograph of any part of Seattle. It represents that part of town from the south line of Cherry Street on the left to the north line of James Street on the right, extending from First to Third Avenues east and west. The buildings shown are the Yesler dwelling in the foreground, and two barns or outbuildings of his. The Hillory Butler Home is back of Yesler's. Opposite the nearest barn is the L.V. Wyckoff house. On its right is the H.A. Smith house. South of James St. is the S.D. Libby house, later that of John Collins. These buildings occupied the ground now covered by immense brick houses, reaching up to sixteen stories in one case. The pole shown stood in front of the Yesler sawmill, where Pioneer Place now is. A V-shaped flume shows in the picture. It brought water down James Street. Seattle's first shade trees, framed in, are seen, or supposed to be seen on the right of the Yesler house. The picture was taken in 1860."

title: Seattle Seahawks hockey team, March 25, 1935
description: Transcribed from photograph: "SEA: 1492: It looks like Seahawks for Championship for Northwest League."" March 25, 1935. Seattle, Washington.- 4,000 hockey fans rattled the rafters of Seattle Ice Arena in a crucial game of the 35 season playoff on Sunday. As it stands the Seattle team has two to one advantage over the Vancouver team and if Seahawks win the next it will be all over. The next game is to be played in Vancouver and if necessary for the fifth game it will be played in Seattle this weekend. L to R. Couch and Manager Frank Foyston, Johnny Houbregs, Moon Mullen, defense, Cameron Proudlock forward, Tony Hemerling, forward, Harold Tabor, forward, Les Whittles, forward, Dave Gilhooly defense and Emmett Venne goalie. Seattle 5, Vancouver 2. Direct service...3/35/35..."

title: Boxing match between Barney Ross and Henry Wood, April 10, 1935
description: Transcribed from photograph: "SEA: 1528. Barney Ross wins decision over Henry Wood in 12 round battle. Seattle, Washington. - When Henry Wood ran into a haymaker. Photo shows left Henry Wood welter weight running into one of Barney Ross's left hooks to the face. New York and Chicago. 4/10/35." According to Seattle Times articles from April 10, the match took place in the Civic Auditorium.

title: Civic Auditorium and Mount Rainier, ca. 1950
description: Photograph taken looking south from lower Queen Anne. The Civic Auditorium and Armory appear on the lower right and Mount Rainier appears in the center.

title: Fire at Brace Lumber Company, May 10, 1935
description: Transcribed from photograph: "SEA: 1588. Strike pickets blamed for hampering firemen at Seattle midnight fire. Seattle, Washington. - With the lumber industry tied up on account labor troubles, it is believed that the $15,000 fire that swept the Brace Lumber Company in ruins and threatened destruction to a big brewery and an oil and gas storage company in the same block, that striking pickets did hamper the work of the fire department of Seattle last night at midnight. Photo shows the raging fire within a few feet of the big brewery. Direct service...5/10/1935..." The 1935 city directory lists the Brace Lumber Company at 925 Valley St.

title: Harry Givan plays for a place in the National Open, May 14, 1935
description: Transcribed from photograph: "SEA: 1612. Northwest all set for two siege guns for National Open. Seattle, Washington. - Harry Givan, ""Amateur"" of Seattle shot a 142 for an [illegible] test to place in the National Open in Pittsburgh June 6,7, and 8th. His 142 was four strokes above par for the 36 holes. Direct service...5/15/35...exclusive..." A May 14, 1935 Seattle Times article identifies the location of the competition at the Seattle Golf Club.

title: View SE from 4th Ave. and Seneca St., 1887
description: Providence Hospital appears in the center of the photograph and the Central School appears above it to the left.

title: Waterfront between Madison and Columbia St., 1887
description: Seattle waterfront between Columbia and Madison Street. YMCA, Budlong's boathouse, and Golden Rule Bazaar.

title: Queen Coffee and Waffle House interior, ca. 1910
description: A 1910 Seattle Times article lists the Waffle House at 119 1/2 W. Main St. This refers to the area west of 1st Ave. that is now called S. Main St. The 119 location corresponds roughly with the present day address of 81 S. Main St.
subjects: Queen Coffee and Waffle House (Seattle, Wash.)

title: Barney Ross, national welter weight, meeting with Howard Dent Jr. from University of Washington, April 2, 1935
description: Transcribed from photograph: "SEA: 1508. Barney Ross arrives in Seattle for match with Henry Wood for title. Seattle, Washington. - Barney Ross, National welter weight has arrived in Seattle to defend his title against Henry Wood, the sturdy Washingtonian in a twelve round bout in Seattle's civic auditorium next week. The champion looks good after a few weeks in the hot springs and there is little doubt that he will come out the heavy man on the tales to put Woods away in a hurry. The first man to greet Ross at the Seattle[Washington] Athletic Club Training quarters was Howard Dent, jr. heavy weight wrestler of the University of Washington. Dent is the blind wrestler who has astonished the world wi th his blind skill in the heavies. His weight is 190 pounds and he is just now slated to take on a bout at Multnomah Club of Portland in the P.N.A. of the A.A.U. wrestling tournament. Photo shows Barney Ross wishing good luck to the blind wrestler on his tour of the Northwest. Direct service...4/2/35...exclusive."

title: Bertha Barkhoff and Zoe Smith, badminton finalists, April 1, 1935
description: Transcribed from photograph: "SEA: 1507. Badminton stars come through according to form. Mrs. Bert Barkhoff [Bertha] and Zoe Smith of Seattle won their place in the State finals at Badminton at Queen Anne Hall last night. After a tour of the Pacific Coast this team came right back and showed the homefolk that their awards were of the first water. They won their set be a score of 15-11 to 15-8. Photo shows Mrs. Barkhoff shooting a back-hand with Miss Zoe Smith backing up. Direct service...4/1/35...exclusive..."

title: Collapsed East Gate at World Fair grounds, February 26, 1962
description: Transcribed from photograph: "Seattle Builders' Work is Un-Fair. What goes up must come down. But workmen erecting the facilities for the Seattle World's Fair are not pleased that their work is undone before the exposition opens. A 40-foot-high laminated wooden arch at the main east entryway collapsed into a heap of splinters Monday. Construction foreman Del Yount said he thought a gust of wind did the damage. The Men were standing under the arch but escaped without injury."

title: 3rd Ave. and Jefferson St. after the fire, July 1889
Paul Satko's children being taken into custody by Juvenile Court, April 25, 1940
description: Transcribed from photograph: "562778. Children taken from Alaska-bound ark. Seattle--Despite efforts to hid in the hold of the home-made Ark of Juneau, bound from Tacoma, Wash. to Alaska, five of the minor children of Paul Satko were taken into temporary custody by the Juvenile Court at Seattle. The action came after a court order was served on Satko, ordering him to turn the children over to authorties on grounds that the ark was unsafe. Here the children are shown on their way to court. Hazel, 18, who wasn't held; Joe, 16; David, 9; Billie, 8; and Grace, 11, partly hidden. Credit line (ACME) 4-26-40." The same photograph appeared in the Seattle Times on April 25, 1940.

title: Cherry St. in the snow, January 10, 1880
description: Seattle in snow. Cherry Street looking northeast. Store signs: Coulter & Shillestad Undertakers, Spring-Beds.

title: Woody Ullin, captain of UW football team, with Coach Phelans, September 15, 1934
description: Transcribed from photograph: "SEA: 1157. The commander and his first lieutenant. Seattle, Washington. - "Here are the tools son. Now go to it" was Coach Phelan's command to Captain Woody Ullin of U. of W. 1934 football squad. Direct service...9/15/34..."

title: Washington Athletic Club swimming team and Mayor Charles Smith, April 18, 1935
description: Transcribed from photograph: "SEA: 1551. City celebrities greet world's champion. Seattle, Washington. - All Seattle turned out today to pay respects to the returning of some thirty athletes who have just returned home after capturing some of the highest honors in the athletic world. The Championship swimming team of the Washington Athletic Club and the Husky crews that made a clean sweep over California's rowing armada. Photo shows Mayor Charles L. Smith greeting the swimmers who swept the eastern boadrs [sic] of records. Left Jack Medica, Olive McKean, Mary Lou Petty, Mayor Charles L. Smith, Doris Buckley, Betty Lee, and Coach Ray Daughters. Direct service...4/18/35...exclusive..."

title: Lake Washington Blvd. looking toward Mt. Rainier, ca. 1925
description: Transcribed from photograph: "A boulevard 50 miles long completely encircles Lake Washington. This view is from the southeastern part of Seattle, with Mount Rainier in the distance."

title: University of Washington Crew team, April 21, 1935
description: Transcribed from photograph: "SEA: 1535. Washington light weight crew nose out Vancouver in spirited race. Seattle, Washington. In a spirited one and one half mile race from Laurelhurst Light to the north end of Mont[lake] Canal, University of Washington nosed out the visiting Vancouver rowing club rack oarsman.  Photo shows the Huskies good half lead length in the lead of the Canadians. Direct Service...4/21/35..."

title: Harry Givan, Scotty Campbell, Johnnie Shields and Bobbie Jones at Seattle Golf Course, November 18, 1934
description: Transcribed from photograph: "SEA: 1272. Four thousand golf fans see fastest amateur golf foursome in country. Seattle, Washington. - When you can bring together four of the finest golfers in the country, it is no wonder that in the neighborhood of 4,000 gold fans turned out to see the match and as well contribute to the associated charities of the district. Photo shows Johnnie [Harry] Givan, Scotty Campbell who defeated Johnnie Shields and Bobbie Jones two and one. Direct service...11/18/34..." A November 18, 1934 Seattle Times article identifies the location of the competition at the Seattle Golf Club.

title: Women in paddleboat on Lake Union, May 15, 1935
description: Transcribed from photograph: "SEA: 1611. Paddle your own canoe "and what fun." Seattle, Washington. - "There is something new under the sun" and that's a sea-worthy paddle boat where one can peddle like a bicycle and keep afloat in the water. Well these days when the bicycle is such a fad with those who want to reduce, this fad sprang into popularity on first demonstration on Lake Union Seattle. It's not necessary to wear a bathing suit at all. Mrs. Frank Curtis obliged and the photographer used good judgement. The other lady is Mrs. Hazel McCraig wife of the inventor, she's not afraid, you will attest riding in her slacks. It's lots of fun riding the swells from the big steamers. Direct service...5/15/35..."

title: Trinity Parish Church, 1874
description: The photograph caption identifies the building as Seattle's first school but it appears to be the Trinity Parish Church located at 3rd Ave. and Jefferson St. The church burned down in the 1889 fire.

title: Walt Rohrscheib, UW football player, September 15, 1934
description: Transcribed from photograph: "SEA. 1158. Big end gets down under the ball well. Seattle, Washington. - Walt Rohrscheib, big Husky end is fast and can get down there under the ball when called on. Direct service...9/15/1934..."

title: University of Washington vs. Idaho football game, September 29, 1934
description: Transcribed from photograph: "SEA: 1186. Idaho show strong team in first two periods. Seattle, Washington. - Cyril Garaghty of Idaho gave the whole Husky team something to worry about. Here we see him reeling off yardage in the first quarter of a game that was a joy to the 18 thousand fans that rooted for the two teams. Direct service...9/19/34..."

title: Truck dumping gravel near 8th Ave. NW and NW 92nd St., November 16, 1948
description: Transcribed from photograph: Date: 11-16; Names: County dumps gravel on 8 NW near. W. 92.; Occasion: Greenwood roads; Photographer: Rote; Reporter: Schulze.""

title: Shirley Frazier, March 13, 1935
description: Transcribed from photograph: "SEA: 1459. Shirley Frazer is best riflewoman in U.S. Seattle, Washington. - 100, 100 100, 99, 99, 100 is the way the scorer chalked up this Co-ed's record in the National shoot. Miss Frazer is a University of Washington co-ed and in her recent record she got 598 out of a possible 600, which is only one point removed from an all time record, she tied last year with Mary Wettach of Carnegie Tech and lost the toss of the coin for first place. Direct service...3/13/35...exclusive..."

Occidental Hotel at 1st Ave. and James St., 1870
description: Transcribed from duplicate photograph's description: "Hotels. Occidental Hotel. Front Street and James Street. Built 1865; demolished about 1883. 1870. 1. Hillory Butler house. 2. Henry A. Atkins house. 3. J. M. Coleman house."

title: A Seattle home and garden, ca. 1925
description: Exact location unknown.

title: Mort Frayn, mayoral candidate, ca. 1969
description: Portrait of Robert Mort Frayn, republican candidate for Seattle mayor who was defeated by Wes Uhlman in 1969.

South Gate at the Alaska-Yukon-Pacific-Exposition, 1909
Former Pacific Northwest Real Estate Association Presidents, 1927
Wooden airplane contest at Green Lake fieldhouse, December 24, 1934
description: Transcribed from photograph: "SEA: 1328. Where our future pilots are made. Seattle, Washington. - Out in Green Lake Fieldhouse they are holding the seasons finals for junior birdmen and here is where the youth of today is getting his first rudiments in the art of flying. This contest is an annual event and the judges are selected from the ranks of the men of authority in this section, the Army, Navy, Marines and civilian flying masters are judges. The winners will receive a handsome trophy and a free trip to the National junior birdmens meet in Detroit in April. Direct service and section #3...12/24/34."

title: Lake Washington Gate at the Alaska-Yukon-Pacific-Exposition, 1909
May Tsutsumoto, Japanese Trade Fair queen, June 17, 1951
description: Transcribed from newspaper caption attached to photograph: "May Tsutsumoto Trade Fair Queen. Charming and beautiful Miss May Tsutsumoto, Seattle Nisei, who is the local queen of the Japanese Trade Fair is 19 years old and was graduated in anthropology from the University of Washington this month."

title: Snack Lunch Cafe, March 7, 1949
description: The restaurant was located on the second floor of the building, accessed by the Marion St. Ferry walkway.

title: Chuck Mucha, University of Washington football player, September 14, 1934
description: Transcribed from photograph: "SEA: 1160. Washington has power in the line. Seattle, Washington. - Chuck Mucha, big guard of University of Washington, is a power in the line with his 195 pounds of drive. Direct service...9/15/34..."

title: Louise Bussell on porch at 1630 36th Ave., ca. 1910
description: Family home of Seattle millionaire C.B. Bussell (full name Charles Baner Bussell), his wife and son, Wallace Adam Bussell. Located at 1630 36th Ave. and constructed in 1892 by George List.

title: Lowman & Hanford Stationery & Printing Company, ca. 1901
description: Lowman & Hanford Stationery & Printing Company in the Lowman and Hanford Building (constructed in 1900). The duplicate photograph identifies the man in the second story window on the right as John Margal. On the street level, the man third from the left is George Miller. The two men on the right are Bob McLellan and James Davidson.

title: Living room in Bussell home at 1630 36th Ave., ca. 1910
description: Family home of Seattle millionaire C.B. Bussell (full name Charles Baner Bussell), his wife and son, Wallace Adam Bussell. Located at 1630 36th Ave. and constructed in 1892 by George List.

title: Schmitz Park woods, ca. 1920
Frank Waterhouse, ca. 1925
description: Waterhouse was a Seattle businessman and civic leader, heavily involved in city activities. He served as president of the Seattle Chamber of Commerce and organized the public campaign to raise funds for the construction of the Olympic Hotel. Additional biographical information is available inside photograph folder.
